04369nam a22006615i 9780674041363DE-B159720210421021438.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210421t20212007mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740413637 a10.4159/97806740413632doi  a(DE-B1597)574533  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aE468.9 -- N438 2007eb 7aHIS0271102bisacsh04a973.71 aNeely, Mark E, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Civil War and the Limits of Destruction /cMark E Neely. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (285 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Mexican-American War -- t2. Price's Raid -- t3. Emperor Maximilian's Black Decree -- t4. The Shenandoah Valley -- t5. The Sand Creek Massacre -- t6. Avenging Andersonville -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustration Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Civil War is often portrayed as the most brutal war in America's history, a premonition of twentieth-century slaughter and carnage. In challenging this view, Mark E. Neely, Jr., considers the war's destructiveness in a comparative context, revealing the sense of limits that guided the conduct of American soldiers and statesmen. Neely begins by contrasting Civil War behavior with U.S. soldiers' experiences in the Mexican War of 1846. He examines Price's Raid in Missouri for evidence of deterioration in the restraints imposed by the customs of war; and in a brilliant analysis of Philip Sheridan's Shenandoah Valley campaign, he shows that the actions of U.S. cavalrymen were selective and controlled. The Mexican war of the 1860s between French imperial forces and republicans provided a new yardstick for brutality: Emperor Maximilian's infamous Black Decree threatened captured enemies with execution. Civil War battles, however, paled in comparison with the unrestrained warfare waged against the Plains Indians. Racial beliefs, Neely shows, were a major determinant of wartime behavior. Destructive rhetoric was rampant in the congressional debate over the resolution to avenge the treatment of Union captives at Andersonville by deliberately starving and freezing to death Confederate prisoners of war. Nevertheless, to gauge the events of the war by the ferocity of its language of political hatred is a mistake, Neely argues. The modern overemphasis on violence in Civil War literature has led many scholars to go too far in drawing close analogies with the twentieth century's "total war" and the grim guerrilla struggles of Vietnam.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 0aDeathxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aRacismxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aViolencexHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aWar casualtiesxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Military / United States.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674041363423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674041363.jpg  a978-3-11-044220-5  HUP eBook Package Backlist 2005-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK